      "title": "Equation and Properties of asymptotes to hyperbola",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Asymptotes&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>If the length of perpendicular drawn from a point on the hyperbola to a straight line tends to zero as the point on moves to infinity. The straight line is called asymptotes.</p><p>Let $y=mx+c$ is the asymptote of the hyperbola $\\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{{{a}^{2}}}-\\frac{{{y}^{2}}}{{{b}^{2}}}$.</p><p>Solving these two we get the quadratic as $\\left( {{b}^{2}}-{{a}^{2}}{{m}^{2}} \\right){{x}^{2}}-2{{a}^{2}}mcx-{{a}^{2}}\\left( {{b}^{2}}+{{c}^{2}} \\right)=0$</p><p>In order that $\\text{y}=\\text{mx}+\\text{c}$ be an asymptote, both roots of equation (1) must approach infinity.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"284\" height=\"259\">&nbsp;</p><p>Which are coefficient of ${{x}^{2}}=0\\And $ coefficient of $x=0$</p><p>or $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ m}=\\pm \\frac{\\text{b}}{\\text{a}}\\And {{\\text{a}}^{2}}\\text{mc}=0\\Rightarrow =0$ …(1)</p><p><strong>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ equation of asymptote are $\\frac{\\text{x}}{\\text{a}}+\\frac{\\text{y}}{\\text{b}}=0~\\And~ \\frac{\\text{x}}{\\text{a}}-\\frac{\\text{y}}{\\text{b}}=0$</strong></p><p>Obviously angle between the asymptotes is $2\\text{ta}{{\\text{n}}^{-1}}\\left( \\text{b}/\\text{a} \\right)$.</p><p>If we draw lines through $\\text{B},\\text{{B}'}$ parallel to the transverse axis and through $\\text{A},\\text{{A}'}$ parallel to the conjugate axis, then $\\text{P}\\left( \\text{a},\\text{b} \\right),\\text{Q}\\left( \\text{a},\\text{b} \\right),\\text{R}\\left( -\\text{a},-\\text{b} \\right)$ and $\\text{S}\\left( \\text{a},-\\text{b} \\right)$ all lie on the asymptotes $\\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{{{a}^{2}}}-\\frac{{{y}^{2}}}{{{b}^{2}}}=0$ so asymptotes are diagonals of the rectangle PQRS. This rectangle is called associated rectangle.</p><p>$\\text{H}\\left( \\frac{{{\\text{x}}^{2}}}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}-\\frac{{{\\text{y}}^{2}}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}=1 \\right),\\text{C}\\left( \\frac{{{\\text{x}}^{2}}}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}-\\frac{{{\\text{y}}^{2}}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}=-1 \\right)\\And \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ A}\\left( \\frac{{{\\text{x}}^{2}}}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}-\\frac{{{\\text{y}}^{2}}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{b}}^{2}}} \\right)=0.$</p><p>Clearly $\\to \\mathbf{C}+\\mathbf{H}=2\\mathbf{A}\\{\\text{H}=$ hyperbola, $\\text{C}=$ Conjugate hyperbola, $\\text{A}=$ Asymptotes $\\}$&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Illustration 19&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Find the equation of the asymptotes of the hyperbola $2{{x}^{2}}-5xy-3{{y}^{2}}-5x-3y-21=0$. Solution&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Since the equation of the pair of asymptotes of the hyperbola differ by the hyperbola by a constant only. So, let the equation of the pair of asymptotes be</p><p>$2{{x}^{2}}-5xy-3{{y}^{2}}-5x-3y+\\lambda =0$ …(i)</p><p>This equation represents a pair of straight lines</p><p><strong>$\\text{abc}+2\\text{fgh}-\\text{a}{{\\text{f}}^{2}}-\\text{b}{{\\text{g}}^{2}}-\\text{c}{{\\text{h}}^{2}}=0$&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Here $:a=2,b=-3,h=-5/2,g=-5/2f=-3/2$ and $c=\\lambda $&nbsp;</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} {} &amp; ~\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }-6\\lambda -\\frac{75}{4}-\\frac{9}{2}+\\frac{75}{4}-\\frac{25}{4}\\lambda =0\\Rightarrow -49\\lambda -75-18+75=0 \\\\ {} &amp; ~\\Rightarrow \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\lambda =-18/49. \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>Putting the value of $\\lambda $ in (i), we get the required equation</p><p>$2{{x}^{2}}-5xy-3{{y}^{2}}-5x-3y-\\frac{18}{49}=0$</p><p><strong>Illustration 20&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>A series of chords of the hyperbola $\\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{{{a}^{2}}}-\\frac{{{y}^{2}}}{{{b}^{2}}}=1$ touch the circle on the line joining the foci as diameter. Show that the locus of the poles of these chords with respect to the hyperbola is $\\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{{{a}^{4}}}+\\frac{{{y}^{2}}}{{{b}^{4}}}=\\frac{1}{{{a}^{2}}+{{b}^{2}}}$.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>The foci of the hyperbola are the points $S\\left( a,0 \\right)$ and ${S}'\\left( -ae,0 \\right)$. Circle on $\\text{S}{{\\text{S}}^{\\text{ }\\!\\!'\\!\\!\\text{ }}}$ as diameter is $\\left( \\text{x}-\\text{ae} \\right)\\left( \\text{x}+\\text{ae} \\right)+{{\\text{y}}^{2}}=0$</p><p>or ${{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}={{a}^{2}}{{e}^{2}}$ …(1)</p><p>If $\\left( h,k \\right)$ be the pole of the chord which touches (1), then its equation is the polar of (h, k) w.r.t. hyperbola</p><p>$\\text{ i}\\text{.e}\\text{. }\\frac{hx}{{{a}^{2}}}-\\frac{ky}{{{b}^{2}}}=1$ …(2)</p><p>Since the line (2) touches the circle (1) therefore perpendicular from center $\\left( 0,0 \\right)$ should be equal to radius ae.</p><p>$\\therefore \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{\\left( \\frac{{{h}^{2}}}{{{a}^{4}}}+\\frac{{{k}^{2}}}{{{b}^{4}}} \\right)}}=ae$</p><p>or $\\frac{{{\\text{h}}^{2}}}{{{\\text{a}}^{4}}}+\\frac{{{\\text{k}}^{2}}}{{{\\text{b}}^{4}}}=\\frac{1}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}{{\\text{e}}^{2}}}=\\frac{1}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}+{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}\\therefore {{\\text{b}}^{2}}={{\\text{a}}^{2}}\\left( {{\\text{e}}^{2}}-1 \\right)$</p><p>Generalizing, the locus of the pole $\\left( h,k \\right)$ is the ellipse $\\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{{{a}^{4}}}+\\frac{{{y}^{2}}}{{{b}^{4}}}=\\frac{1}{{{a}^{2}}+{{b}^{2}}}$</p><p><strong>Illustration 21&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Show that the locus of poles with respect to the parabola ${{y}^{2}}=4ax$ of tangents to the hyperbola ${{x}^{2}}-{{y}^{2}}={{a}^{2}}$ is the ellipse $4{{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}=4{{a}^{2}}$.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution: </strong>Any tangent to the hyperbola ${{x}^{2}}-{{y}^{2}}={{a}^{2}}$ is</p><p>$x\\text{sec}q-y\\text{tan}\\theta =a$</p><p>$x-y \\sin \\theta=a \\cos \\theta$ …(1)</p><p>If its pole w.r.t. parabola ${{y}^{2}}=4\\text{ax}$ be $\\left( \\text{h},\\text{k} \\right)$ then it is same as $\\text{ky}=2\\text{a}\\left( \\text{x}+\\text{h} \\right)$</p><p>Or $2\\text{ax}-\\text{ky}=-2\\text{ah}$ …(2)</p><p>Compare (1) and (2), $\\frac{1}{2\\text{a}}=\\frac{\\text{sin}\\theta }{\\text{k}}=\\frac{\\text{cos}\\theta }{-2\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ h}}$</p><p>Elimination $\\theta $ by $\\text{cos}\\theta +\\text{si}{{\\text{n}}^{2}}\\theta =1$</p><p>${{\\text{k}}^{2}}+4\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{h}}^{2}}=4{{\\text{a}}^{2}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ Locus }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ is }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }4{{\\text{x}}^{2}}+{{\\text{y}}^{2}}=4{{\\text{a}}^{2}}.$</p><p><strong>Illustration 22&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>A series of hyperbolas are such that the length of their transverse axis is $2\\text{a}$. Show that the locus of a point $P$ on each such that its distance from the transverse axis is equal to its distance from an asymptote is the curve ${{\\left( {{x}^{2}}-{{y}^{2}} \\right)}^{2}}=4{{x}^{2}}\\left( {{x}^{2}}-{{a}^{2}} \\right)$.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Let the hyperbola be $\\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{{{a}^{2}}}-\\frac{{{y}^{2}}}{{{b}^{2}}}=1$ and one of its asymptotes is $\\frac{x}{a}-\\frac{y}{b}=0$</p><p>Here $\\text{a}$ is given but $\\text{b}$ is not known. Choose any point $\\left( \\text{h},\\text{k} \\right)$ on the hyperbola.</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\frac{{{\\text{h}}^{2}}}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}-\\frac{{{\\text{k}}^{2}}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}=1$ …(1)</p><p>By given condition $\\text{k}=\\frac{\\frac{\\text{h}}{\\text{a}}-\\frac{\\text{k}}{\\text{b}}}{\\sqrt{\\left( \\frac{1}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}+\\frac{1}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{b}}^{2}}} \\right)}}$</p><p>Or $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{k}}^{2}}\\left( \\frac{1}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}+\\frac{1}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{b}}^{2}}} \\right)={{\\left( \\frac{\\text{h}}{\\text{a}}-\\frac{\\text{k}}{\\text{b}} \\right)}^{2}}$ …(2)</p><p>In order to find the locus of $\\left( h,k \\right)$ we have to eliminate unknown ${{b}^{2}}$. Now form (2)</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} {} &amp; \\frac{{{\\text{k}}^{2}}}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}-\\frac{{{\\text{h}}^{2}}}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}=\\frac{2\\text{hk}}{\\text{ab}} \\\\ {} &amp; {{\\left( {{\\text{k}}^{2}}-{{\\text{h}}^{2}} \\right)}^{2}}=\\frac{4{{\\text{a}}^{2}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{h}}^{2}}{{\\text{k}}^{2}}}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{b}}^{2}}} \\\\ {} &amp; \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ or }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\left( {{\\text{k}}^{2}}-{{\\text{h}}^{2}} \\right)=4{{\\text{a}}^{2}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{h}}^{2}}\\left( \\frac{{{\\text{h}}^{2}}}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}-1 \\right),\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ by }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ (1) }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ } \\\\ {} &amp; \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ or }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\left( {{\\text{x}}^{2}}-{{\\text{y}}^{2}} \\right)=4{{\\text{x}}^{2}}\\left( {{\\text{x}}^{2}}-{{\\text{a}}^{2}} \\right) \\\\ {} &amp; \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ is }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ the }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ required }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ locus}\\text{. }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ } \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p><strong>Illustration 23&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Prove that the product of the perpendiculars from any point on the hyperbola $\\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{{{a}^{2}}}-\\frac{{{y}^{2}}}{{{b}^{2}}}=1$&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>to its asymptotes is equal to $\\frac{{{a}^{2}}{{b}^{2}}}{{{a}^{2}}+{{b}^{2}}}$.&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Let $\\left( a\\text{sec}\\theta ,b\\text{tan}\\theta \\right)$ be any point on the hyperbola $\\frac{{{x}^{2}}}{{{a}^{2}}}-\\frac{{{y}^{2}}}{{{b}^{2}}}=1$</p><p>The equations of the asymptotes of the given hyperbola are $\\frac{x}{a}-\\frac{y}{b}=0$ and $\\frac{x}{a}+\\frac{y}{b}=0$</p><p>Now, ${{\\text{p}}_{1}}=$ length of the perpendicular from $\\left( \\text{asec}\\theta ,\\text{btan}\\theta \\right)$ on $\\frac{\\text{x}}{\\text{a}}-\\frac{\\text{y}}{\\text{b}}=0=\\frac{\\text{sec}\\theta -\\text{tan}\\theta }{\\sqrt{\\frac{1}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}+\\frac{1}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}}}$</p><p>and, ${{\\text{p}}_{2}}=$ length of the perpendicular from on $\\left( \\text{asec}\\theta ,\\text{btan}\\theta \\right)$ on $\\frac{\\text{x}}{\\text{a}}+\\frac{\\text{y}}{\\text{b}}=0=\\frac{\\text{sec}\\theta +\\text{tan}\\theta }{\\sqrt{\\frac{1}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}+\\frac{1}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}}}$ $\\therefore {{\\text{p}}_{1}}{{\\text{p}}_{2}}=\\frac{\\text{se}{{\\text{c}}^{2}}\\theta -\\text{ta}{{\\text{n}}^{2}}\\theta }{\\frac{1}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}}+\\frac{1}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}}=\\frac{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}{{{\\text{a}}^{2}}+{{\\text{b}}^{2}}}$</p>",
